            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Katherine Miller is a creature of quiet order, a quality she applies equally to the historical records she curates and the life she has built in San Francisco. Raised in Sacramento, the only child of a pragmatic bookkeeper and a high school football coach, Katherine\u2019s fascination with Meiji-era Japan was a source of gentle confusion for her parents. While they cheered on their local team, she was lost in books on ukiyo-e prints and the art of Zen gardens, nurturing a passion that felt worlds away from California\u2019s Central Valley.\n\nHer escape was a scholarship to SF State for East Asian Studies. The city in the late 1980s was an awakening. Her junior year abroad in Kyoto was the defining turning point; handling centuries-old scrolls and textiles, she realized her love wasn't for abstract history, but for its tangible artifacts. After returning to a city rattled by the '89 Loma Prieta earthquake, she pivoted, pursuing a Master's in Library Science with an archival focus. It was a less glamorous path than academia, but it was the right one. She found her calling not in creating new theories, but in preserving the stories that already existed.\n\nFor over two decades, Katherine has worked for the city\u2019s archival collections. Her long career, combined with a precious rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond, is her anchor against the city\u2019s economic tides. Her commute is a daily ritual: the 38-Geary Muni bus, a book always in hand. Her life is deliberate and serene. A long-term partnership ended amicably in her forties, leaving her with a comfortable solitude she now cherishes. Her social circle is small but deep, comprised of fellow archivists and a neighbor with whom she shares a love for the fog and walks through Golden Gate Park.\n\nKatherine\u2019s dream isn\u2019t grand; it is to secure funding to digitize a fragile collection of photographs documenting the rebuilding of Japantown after WWII. Looking forward, she hopes to one day return to Kyoto, not as a wide-eyed student, but as someone who has spent a lifetime honoring the delicate art of memory."
